 {"id":"bd-yx9r","title":"Reopened full-crate parity closure against /dp/asupersync export surface","description":"The previously closed roadmap mostly covered kernel and selective deferred surfaces, but /dp/asupersync/src/lib.rs still exports many major module families that are not materially present in the ANSI C tree: config, decoding, epoch, evidence, evidence_sink, gen_server, http, io, link, migration, monitor, observability, obligation, record, remote, service, session, spork, transport, types, web, plus feature/platform modules such as cli, database, tls, grpc, messaging, and server. This epic reopens parity planning at the crate level instead of stopping at kernel semantics.","design":"Use /dp/asupersync/README.md, /dp/asupersync/src/lib.rs, the upstream module tree, and the local deferred-surface docs as the primary evidence base. The graph should separate: (1) truth-maintenance tasks that correct the parity narrative, (2) foundation tracks needed before protocol/application stacks, and (3) end-state acceptance/gating work that proves crate-level parity or explicitly records remaining deliberate exclusions. Every implementation track must carry unit tests, integration/conformance fixtures where possible, and logged e2e or smoke artifacts.","acceptance_criteria":"A. The reopened backlog explicitly covers every major Rust export family that remains absent or only stubbed in ANSI C.\\nB. The graph distinguishes foundational blockers from higher-surface protocol/application work.\\nC. Each child issue stores enough background and verification detail that the original markdown plans are unnecessary.\\nD. Final acceptance requires crate-level parity evidence rather than kernel-only success criteria.","notes":"Primary upstream evidence: /dp/asupersync/src/lib.rs, /dp/asupersync/README.md, and upstream module directories such as src/http, src/web, src/grpc, src/service, src/transport, src/distributed, src/database, src/messaging, src/types, src/record, src/obligation, src/lab, src/trace, and src/runtime/reactor. Local evidence that the old closure was too narrow: docs/DEFERRED_SURFACES.md, docs/DEFERRED_SURFACE_REGISTER.md, and docs/SELECTIVE_SURFACE_PORTING_QUEUE.md.","status":"open","priority":0,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:15.573296808Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-13T22:29:34.427618288Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","core-parity","crate-parity","reopened","upstream-gap"]}
 {"id":"bd-yx9r.1","title":"Rebuild authoritative upstream export-gap inventory and parity truth table","description":"Build a fresh, source-backed gap inventory that compares the Rust crate's exported module surface and README claims against the actual ANSI C public headers, source directories, docs, examples, and tests. This is needed because the prior backlog closure treated kernel parity as if it implied crate parity.","design":"Inventory should enumerate each upstream exported family, classify current ANSI C state as absent, stub-only, partial, or substantive, link the relevant local files if any, and record the concrete user-facing gap. The output should be detailed enough to drive future prioritization without reopening lib.rs.","acceptance_criteria":"A. Every major Rust export family is classified against the ANSI C tree with evidence.\\nB. Stub-only or misleadingly named local modules are explicitly called out.\\nC. The inventory identifies which higher-surface tracks depend on networking, runtime-reactor, trace/lab, or type-system completion.\\nD. The resulting backlog can be audited against this inventory.","notes":"Must cover portable, feature-gated, and platform-specific modules separately. Include examples, CLI, test-helper, and docs surfaces when they materially affect user expectations.","status":"closed","priority":0,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:16.255862790Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-14T00:46:06.691731999Z","closed_at":"2026-03-14T00:46:06.636636775Z","close_reason":"Completed: refreshed docs/RUST_EXPORTED_SURFACE_INVENTORY.md with a 2026-03-14 crate-vs-C truth table covering portable, feature-gated, platform-gated, and adjacent contract surfaces, including absent/stub-only/partial/substantive classifications and shipped-vs-tree notes","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","core-parity","crate-parity","docs","inventory","truth"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:16.255862790Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"bd-yx9r.10","title":"HTTP, web, and gRPC application-surface parity","description":"The largest obvious crate-level gap is the application protocol surface: HTTP/1-2-3, web routing/middleware/extract/session/static/SSE/multipart/security helpers, and gRPC server/client/codec/reflection/health support. These families are front-and-center in the upstream tree and README expectations.","design":"This epic should port them as coherent, layered public modules instead of scattering one-off examples or stubs.","acceptance_criteria":"A. ANSI C exposes substantive HTTP/web/gRPC families with clear layering over network, service, and advanced transport foundations.\\nB. Tests cover protocol correctness, routing/security behavior, and logged end-to-end scenarios.\\nC. User-facing examples and smoke packs exist for representative server/client workflows.","notes":"Primary upstream references: src/http/*, src/web/*, and src/grpc/*.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"epic","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:39.237268870Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-13T22:29:34.880924472Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["conformance","crate-parity","grpc","http","web"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:39.237268870Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:39:14.669058190Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:39:15.730884551Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:39:16.790793355Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","title":"Implement HTTP body/pool/common plus HTTP/1-2-3 parity","description":"Port the broad HTTP surface: bodies, pools, compression/common helpers, HTTP/1 codecs/server/client/listener/stream types, and HTTP/2 plus HTTP/3 lifecycle/flow components.","design":"The implementation must carry concrete tests and logged scenario coverage rather than stop at type shells. Pay special attention to stream lifecycle, backpressure, compression, and upgrade/error cases.","acceptance_criteria":"A. Public HTTP modules exist across H1/H2/H3 families with coherent error and stream semantics.\\nB. Unit/integration tests cover framing, connection lifecycle, pool behavior, and failure paths.\\nC. E2E scenarios exercise at least one HTTP client/server flow for each major family with detailed artifacts.","notes":"Depends on E2, F, and G1.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:40.669743102Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-13T22:28:46.392685673Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["crate-parity","http"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:27:20.029128652Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.10","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:40.669743102Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.18.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:28:46.391773357Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:27:21.017538664Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.3","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:27:22.003656468Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.7.2","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:39:44.898024373Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.9.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:39:46.225744380Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
+{"id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","title":"Implement HTTP body/pool/common plus HTTP/1-2-3 parity","description":"Port the broad HTTP surface: bodies, pools, compression/common helpers, HTTP/1 codecs/server/client/listener/stream types, and HTTP/2 plus HTTP/3 lifecycle/flow components.","design":"The implementation must carry concrete tests and logged scenario coverage rather than stop at type shells. Pay special attention to stream lifecycle, backpressure, compression, and upgrade/error cases.","acceptance_criteria":"A. Public HTTP modules exist across H1/H2/H3 families with coherent error and stream semantics.\\nB. Unit/integration tests cover framing, connection lifecycle, pool behavior, and failure paths.\\nC. E2E scenarios exercise at least one HTTP client/server flow for each major family with detailed artifacts.","notes":"Depends on E2, F, and G1.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:40.669743102Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-19T03:28:12.790684636Z","closed_at":"2026-03-19T03:28:12.789345841Z","close_reason":"HTTP body/pool/common + HTTP/1-2-3 parity implemented: http.c/h with method/status/version enums, header management (case-insensitive), body types, request/response builders, and connection pool with acquire/release/reuse. 19 unit tests passing. 129 total test suites.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"labels":["crate-parity","http"],"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:27:20.029128652Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.10","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-13T20:38:40.669743102Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9r.10.1","depends_on_id":"bd-yx9r.18.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-03-13T22:28:46.391773357Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"bd-yx9